Two-way factorial anova

response ~ constant + A + B + A*B + error

\[ \begin{aligned} y_{ij} = \mu + A_i + B_j + (AB)_{ij} + \epsilon_{ij} \\ \end{aligned} \]

  • \(\mu\) = population mean across treatments
  • \(A\) = treatment A, with levels \(i\)
  • \(B\) = tratment B, with levels \(j\)
  • \((AB)_{ij}\) = interaction betwen treatment A and B

Factors A and B are considered the main effects of interest

Draw your avocado x bacon plot. Then discuss with neighbor.

Exercise

Analyze and interpret the class avocado-bacon data!

dat <- read_csv(paste(repo_url, 
                      "class_data_avocado_bacon.csv", sep = ""))
dat_long <- dat %>%
  gather(key = treatment, value = tastiness, a0_b0:a1_b1) %>% 
  mutate(avocado = ifelse(grepl("a0", treatment) == TRUE, 
                          "no avocado", "avocado"), 
         bacon = ifelse(grepl("b0", treatment) == TRUE, 
                        "no bacon", "bacon"))

ggplot(dat_long, aes(treatment, tastiness)) + geom_boxplot()
ggplot(dat_long, aes(avocado, tastiness, fill = bacon)) + geom_boxplot()

Random avocado and bacon data

Whitlock & Schluter 2015

In a factorial design, every level of one factor is present in combination with every level of the other factor(s).

Not true for a nested design.

Sketch a crossed vs nested design

Factor 1: 2 levels (A, B)
Factor 2: 4 levels, (a, b, c, d)
n = 4 replicates per factor combination

In a factorial design, every level of one factor is present in combination with every level of the other factor(s).

Factor 1: 2 levels (A, B)
Factor 2: 4 levels, (a, b, c, d)
n = 4 replicates per factor combination

Schielzeth & Nakagawa 2013

Degrees of freedom

Source df
Among \(A_i\) a -1
Among \(B_j\) b - 1
Interaction \((AxB)_{ij}\) (a-1)(b-1)
Within ab(n-1)
Total abn - 1

Assumptions

  • Errors \(\epsilon_{ij}\) are independent

  • Within each combination of factors A & B, errors \(\epsilon_{ij}\) are distributed normally and have equal variance

  • ANOVA and F-test assume balanced data

Types of factorial ANOVA

Model 1: all factors are fixed

Model 2: all factors are random

Model 3: one factor fixed, one factor random (at least)

Model 1, 2 or 3? Consequences for F-ratio

Zar 2010

Factorial ANOVA: example

How do small grazers (limpets and snails) affect the abundance of Mazzaella at two different tidal heights?

Factor A: Herbivore treatment

  • control (no copper fencing)
  • herbivore exclusion (copper fencing)
  • a = 2

Factor B: Tidal height

  • mid-intertidal zone
  • low-intertidal zone
  • b = 2

Reponse: percent cover of algae (square-root transformed)

  • n = 16 per treatment combination

Fixed or random effects?

Load the data

# Packages
library(tidyverse); library(broom)
theme_set(theme_bw(base_size = 14) + 
            theme(panel.grid = element_blank())) 

# Set the web address where R will look for files from this repository
repo_url <- "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/elahi/xdp/master/data/"
dat <- read_csv(paste(repo_url, 
                      "chap18e3IntertidalAlgae.csv", sep = ""))
dat <- dat %>% 
  mutate(herbivores = ifelse(herbivores == "minus", 
                             "absent", "present"), # renaming levels
         herbivores = as.factor(herbivores), 
         height = as.factor(height))

ggplot(dat, aes(herbivores, sqrtArea, fill = height)) + geom_boxplot()

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{algae} = \mu + \text{herbivores} + \text{height} + \text{herbivores x height} \\ \end{aligned} \]

m0 <- lm(sqrtArea ~ herbivores + height, data = dat)
m1 <- lm(sqrtArea ~ herbivores + height + herbivores:height, data = dat)
m1 <- lm(sqrtArea ~ herbivores * height, data = dat)

Always check to make sure that the F-ratio is calculated appropriately!

Model diagnostics

Check that residuals, within treatment combinations,

  • have a nearly normal distribution
  • no pattern (trend, unequal variance)
par(mfrow = c(2,2)); plot(m1)
dat$resids <- m1$residuals
ggplot(dat, aes(herbivores, resids)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, size = 3) + facet_wrap(~ height)
